Part II - Flights dataset¶

by DA MATHA Joris Axel¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this presentation i will try to answer effectively to the three questions (Are there certain destination or arrival cities that experience more delays or cancellations? What are the main factors behind the cancellation of flights? What are the preferred times for flights to occur?) Firstly we will have a global view of all delayed flights and how they are distributed in dataset. After, we will see have more visibility about cancelled flights in dataset. Then we will apreciate the real impact of great factors delays followed by cancellation factors impact according to city and time. Finally we will have a final overview of flights delay per month on 10 most frequent cities/countries.

Dataset Overview¶

This dataset explores reporting flights in US including carriers, arrival and depature delays and reasons for delays, from 1987 to 2008. But my investigations are focused the the last 4 years contents (2004-2008). The main variables which contributed to my investigations are the Origins, Destinations, the flights delay and cancellation factors.

# load in the dataset into a pandas dataframe
df = pd.read_csv('./flights_dataset.csv')
In [3]:
cols_selected = ['Year', 'Month', 'DayofMonth', 'DayOfWeek', 'ArrDelay',
       'DepDelay','Origin','Dest','Cancelled', 'CancellationCode', 'Diverted', 'CarrierDelay',
       'WeatherDelay', 'NASDelay', 'SecurityDelay', 'LateAircraftDelay']
df= df[cols_selected]
df['Cancelled'].replace({0: 'Not Cancelled', 1: 'Cancelled'},inplace =True)
df['CancellationCode'].replace({'A':'Carrier','B':'Weather', 'C':'NAS', 'D':'Security'}, inplace =True)
df['Month'].replace({1:'JAN',2:'FEB',3:'MAR',4:'APR',5:'MAY',6:'JUN',7:'JUL',8:'AUG',9:'SEP',10:'OCT',11:'NOV',12:'DEC'}, inplace=True)
df['DayOfWeek'].replace({1:'Monday',2:'Tuesday',3:'Wednesday',4:'Thursday',5:'Friday',6:'Saturday',7:'Sunday'},inplace = True)
df.DayOfWeek.value_counts()

# convert Month, Day of week into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'Month': ['JAN','FEB','MAR','APR','MAY','JUN','JUL','AUG','SEP','OCT','NOV','DEC'],
                    'DayOfWeek': ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday'],
                    'CancellationCode': ['Carrier','Weather','NAS','Security']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    df[var] = df[var].astype(ordered_var)

df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
df_1 = df.query('DepDelay >= 0 | DepDelay != DepDelay')
sorted_dest = df_1['Dest'].value_counts()[:10]
df_dest_sorted = df_1[df['Dest'].isin(sorted_dest.index)]
sorted_org = df_1['Origin'].value_counts()[:10]
df_org_sorted = df_1[df_1['Origin'].isin(sorted_org.index)]
df_flights = pd.concat([df_org_sorted,df_dest_sorted],ignore_index=True)
df_flights.drop_duplicates(inplace = True)

# compute the logarithm of price to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

df_dest_sorted['Log_ArrDelay'] = df_dest_sorted[df_dest_sorted['ArrDelay']!= 0]['ArrDelay'].apply(log_trans)
df_org_sorted['Log_DepDelay'] = df_org_sorted[df_org_sorted['DepDelay']!= 0]['DepDelay'].apply(log_trans)
delay_params =['DepDelay','ArrDelay']
factor_delays =['LateAircraftDelay','NASDelay']
xlabels =['Departure Delay (mn)','Arrival Delay (mn)']
delay_params_log =['Log_DepDelay','Log_ArrDelay']
ylabels = ['Late Aircraft Delay (mn)','NAS Delay (mn)']
df_list =[df_org_sorted,df_dest_sorted]

Note that the above cells have been set as "Skip"-type slides. That means that when the notebook is rendered as http slides, those cells won't show up.

Distribution of Arrival Delays and Departure Delays of flights¶

There are more than 24 Millions flights in the dataset with at least 20 features. The distribution is unimodal about the arrival delay time and slightly skewed at right. But that's normal because most of flight haven't delay at arrival.We can notice that the negative Arrival delay means that the airplane arrived early. Same remark on departure delays.

fig, ax =plt.subplots(ncols =2,figsize =[15,8])
for i in range(len(delay_params)):
    binsize = 10
    bins = np.arange(df[delay_params[i]].min(), df[delay_params[i]].max()+binsize, binsize) 
    sb.histplot(data = df, x = delay_params[i],bins = bins,ax = ax[i])
    ax[i].set_yticks([0,1e6,2e6,3e6,4e6,7e6])
    ax[i].set_yticklabels([0,'1M','2M','3M','4M','7M'])
    ax[i].set_xlim(-50,400)
    ax[i].set_xlabel(delay_params[i])
    ax[i].set_title('Distribution of flights '+delay_params[i])

Number of flights cancelled on 10 most common destinations¶

Before going in detail into dataset to filter out main factors responsible of flights cancellation, let's have a global view of dataset content. That could be very difficult for passengers to accept the departures in advance. So i removed the negative departures delays from dataset. The higher number of cancelled flights is on ORD followed by ATL and DFW.

Factors linked to flights late at departure and arrival¶

During my investigations, i understood that delay factors are independants between them but i discovered that from almost 100 min delay of a late aircraft, the depature could be delayed slowly up more than 500 min.The impact of NAS Delay on arrival delay is more important. Even with 10 min of NAS Delay , we can have more than 400 min of arrival delay.From 40 min of NAS Delay the arrival delay can quickly grow up to more than 500 min.

Factors linked to flights cancellation¶

Most of flights on ORD are cancelled due to NAS and on ATL due to Carrier. However, Weather is also a major factor of cancellation of flights no matter the destination. That's confirmed on the second figure, especially for IAH. The majority of flights are could be cancelled due to weather especially in January, February and December just after carrier factor.

Arrival and departure delays by month on 10 most popular cities/countries¶

The majority of delayed flights at arrival are on June and July at EWR and ATL. On another hand, the majority of flights delayed at the depature are on december, june and july at ORD and EWR, followed by ATL.

Submission¶

If you are using classroom workspace, you can choose from the following two ways of submission:

  1. Submit from the workspace. Make sure you have removed the example project from the /home/workspace directory. You must submit the following files:
    • Part_I_notebook.ipynb
    • Part_I_notebook.html or pdf
    • Part_II_notebook.ipynb
    • Part_I_slides.html
    • README.md
    • dataset (optional)
  1. Submit a zip file on the last page of this project lesson. In this case, open the Jupyter terminal and run the command below to generate a ZIP file. 
    zip -r my_project.zip .
    The command abobve will ZIP every file present in your /home/workspace directory. Next, you can download the zip to your local, and follow the instructions on the last page of this project lesson.
